{
  "answer": "The *Manusmṛti* (Laws of Manu), Chapter 5, contains these arguments.[^1]\n\nAnimals slain at a sacrifice attain higher rebirths:  \n> Herbs, animals, trees, beasts, and birds, which have met their death for the sake of a sacrifice, attain higher states of existence again. // Mn_5.40 //[^2]\n\n'In a sacrifice, killing is not killing':  \n> Animals were created for the sake of sacrifice by the Self-existent One himself; the sacrifice is for the prosperity of this whole world; **therefore, in a sacrifice, killing is not killing**. // Mn_5.39 //[^3]\n\nOne who kills an animal needlessly will suffer a violent death in as many future births as the slain animal had hairs:  \n> **As many hairs as the animal has, so many times does the one who kills it for no reason suffer a violent death in future births**. // Mn_5.38 //[^4]\n\n[^1]: *Manusmṛti*, [Chapter 5](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/05/translation/).\n\n[^2]: *Manusmṛti*, [Mn_5.40](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/05/translation/#p-aa01df).\n\n[^3]: *Manusmṛti*, [Mn_5.39](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/05/translation/#p-d81302).\n\n[^4]: *Manusmṛti*, [Mn_5.38](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/05/translation/#p-42b5e1).",
